<i>here's your host, Jonathan Ross.</i>

00:28.467 --> 00:30.700
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

00:36.667 --> 00:38.067
Thank you, so much.

00:39.633 --> 00:42.600
Welcome to <i>Penn &amp; Teller: Fool Us.</i>

00:42.667 --> 00:44.567
The show with illusions more convincing

00:44.633 --> 00:46.700
than the story you told
your partner about what you did

00:46.767 --> 00:48.433
the last time you came to Las Vegas.

00:48.800 --> 00:52.433
Backstage are some
of the greatest magicians in the world.

00:52.500 --> 00:55.200
Now, they're not here to fool me
because, of course, that would be easy.

00:55.267 --> 00:58.800
Why, only last year, I gave all
my life savings to a Nigerian prince.

00:58.867 --> 00:59.867
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

01:00.267 --> 01:03.367
No, tonight our acts have the harder task
of trying to dupe the un-dupable,

01:03.433 --> 01:05.233
the great Penn and Teller.

01:05.367 --> 01:07.967
Now, leaving Teller speechless
is pretty much a given,

01:08.067 --> 01:11.167
but having Penn shut up means
you've done something really remarkable.

01:11.233 --> 01:13.033
Here they are right now.
Will you please go crazy

01:13.100 --> 01:17.200
for magic's version of Donnie and Marie.
It is, of course, Penn and Teller!

01:17.667 --> 01:19.533
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

01:25.267 --> 01:28.500
Great to see you, as always.
Penn, fabulous, you're looking great.

01:28.567 --> 01:29.567
Thank you, Jon.

01:30.133 --> 01:32.767
I'm a little bit country.
He's a little bit rock 'n' roll.

01:32.833 --> 01:35.500
That's the way we like to roll.
So, ladies and gentlemen,

01:35.567 --> 01:37.300
I'm gonna ask you guys
to get comfortable in your seats

01:37.367 --> 01:38.733
so we can get on with the show.
It's Penn and Teller,

01:38.800 --> 01:40.533
-ladies and gentlemen!
-(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

01:53.000 --> 01:55.667
Without further ado,
let's get the show going,

01:55.867 --> 01:57.767
and let's bring out our first magician.

02:02.333 --> 02:04.667
Hi, I'm Jon Armstrong,
and I'm originally from Orlando, Florida.

02:04.733 --> 02:07.900
<i>I am dyslexic, and school</i>
<i>was impossible for me.</i>

02:08.133 --> 02:11.700
But then I discovered comics,
and I could really enjoy them.

02:11.833 --> 02:13.767
<i>Growing up,</i>
<i>I always wanted to be a superhero.</i>

02:14.433 --> 02:16.200
Actually, I still want to be a superhero.

02:16.867 --> 02:21.267
<i>One of my proudest achievements was that</i>
<i>I was able to co-write my own comic book.</i>

02:21.367 --> 02:23.267
<i>It's about a magician like myself.</i>

02:23.333 --> 02:24.467
Hold out your hand.

02:25.867 --> 02:28.533
<i>I'm attracted to magic</i>
<i>and comics for the same reason.</i>

02:29.100 --> 02:32.533
They're both these amazing
sort of art forms that allow the author,

02:32.600 --> 02:37.700
the creator, to give their audience
a world they never thought was possible.

02:41.900 --> 02:43.600
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

02:46.000 --> 02:49.033
This next performer became
the resident magician at Disney World

02:49.100 --> 02:51.900
when he was just 20 years old,
which means we know he can fool

02:51.967 --> 02:54.967
a giant mouse and a talking duck,
but can he fool Penn and Teller?

02:55.033 --> 02:57.033
Please welcome Jon Armstrong!

02:57.400 --> 02:58.400
(APPLAUSE)

02:58.600 --> 03:01.533
Thank you!
Wow, this is amazing.

03:02.167 --> 03:03.733
It's an honor to be here.

03:03.800 --> 03:05.067
I was wondering
if I can get you two gentlemen

03:05.133 --> 03:07.300
to come and join me up here.
And Jonathan, you seem nice enough.

03:07.367 --> 03:09.300
-I'll go here. You go there?
-Yeah, if you don't mind.

03:09.367 --> 03:10.367
PENN: It frightens me.
JONATHAN: I'll go here.

03:10.433 --> 03:13.133
Uh, it's actually not me that's here
to fool you. It's this little guy here.

03:13.200 --> 03:16.167
It's a suction cup attached
to a tiny dowel rod.

03:16.233 --> 03:17.233
It is adorable.

03:17.333 --> 03:18.567
I know.

03:18.633 --> 03:20.200
What I'm gonna show you
is the most impressive thing

03:20.267 --> 03:21.500
you'll ever see in your entire life.

03:21.567 --> 03:24.200
Seriously, from this moment on,
your lives are gonna go downhill.

03:24.400 --> 03:26.733
When I do this for little kids,
I feel bad.

03:27.133 --> 03:28.200
All right, watch.

03:29.767 --> 03:30.767
Thank you.

03:31.433 --> 03:32.867
All right, all right.

03:33.000 --> 03:35.600
Just kidding, but you can see
the little suction cup, you know,

03:35.667 --> 03:39.567
that it's only supposed
to pick up one card at a time, right?

03:39.633 --> 03:40.700
That's how it works.

03:40.767 --> 03:43.167
But if you give it
a little bit of a rev, watch...

03:44.667 --> 03:45.667
Till it works.

03:46.100 --> 03:48.000
You guys just see this every day?
Is that the idea?

03:48.067 --> 03:50.833
Check this out, check this out.
Make sure there's sticky tape,

03:50.900 --> 03:51.900
nothing like that on 'em.

03:51.967 --> 03:54.067
Check out the plunger.
Make sure it's a perfectly ordinary,

03:54.133 --> 03:56.967
tiny plunger that you'd find
in any Barbie dream home.

03:57.033 --> 03:58.400
-Yeah.
-Yes, okay, good.

03:58.467 --> 03:59.500
Take it back.

03:59.567 --> 04:01.967
We're in America.
What do we care about? Bulk.

04:04.233 --> 04:07.067
(WHISPERING)
You can do it, buddy. You can do it.

04:07.933 --> 04:08.933
PENN: Oh!

04:09.067 --> 04:10.400
JON: Tiny plunger.

04:10.500 --> 04:11.500
(APPLAUSE)

04:12.833 --> 04:17.300
Now, the tiny plunger, he is educated,
he is learned, he understands things.

04:17.367 --> 04:18.367
I'll show you what I mean by that.

04:18.433 --> 04:21.600
Jonathan, give me
a number between 10 and 20.

04:21.666 --> 04:23.867
-Uh, 15.
-Fifteen. Again!

04:23.933 --> 04:24.967
Ready? Watch.

04:26.533 --> 04:28.300
Please count those out loud,
down to the table.

04:28.367 --> 04:32.233
JONATHAN: One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight, nine,

04:32.300 --> 04:34.933
10, 11, 12, 13, 14,

04:35.000 --> 04:36.600
-15!
-Fifteen exactly!

04:38.067 --> 04:40.600
JON: Tiny plunger. Tiny plunger.

04:42.100 --> 04:44.533
Now, he just doesn't
understand card quantity.

04:44.600 --> 04:45.967
He understands card identity,

04:46.033 --> 04:48.167
the difference between
one card and another card.

04:48.233 --> 04:49.533
So let me show you what I'm talking about.

04:49.600 --> 04:51.333
If you could just touch
one of those for me, please.

04:51.433 --> 04:53.433
-Just grab it right out.
-PENN: Okay, sure.

04:53.500 --> 04:55.133
Excellent, and, uh, what's gonna happen,

04:55.200 --> 04:56.533
is take the card and show it around.

04:56.600 --> 04:58.833
But I'm gonna have to hide
the plunger so he doesn't see.

04:59.200 --> 05:00.767
Everybody see the card? Yes?

05:01.200 --> 05:03.300
Good. I'm gonna put the plunger back.
Don't let him see.

05:03.400 --> 05:04.500
He tried to look at it.

05:04.567 --> 05:07.167
Yeah, okay. (LAUGHS)
And place it back inside there for me.

05:07.467 --> 05:08.533
Good. Okay.

05:09.267 --> 05:11.433
The tiny plunger will now memorize

05:11.867 --> 05:13.867
the entire deck of cards.

05:15.100 --> 05:16.867
(LAUGHING)

05:17.900 --> 05:19.233
He has done so.

05:20.367 --> 05:23.233
Please whisper the name
of your card to the tiny plunger.

05:26.000 --> 05:27.567
(LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE)

05:30.800 --> 05:33.000
Most people just pick it up,
but that was pretty awesome.

05:33.633 --> 05:35.000
But the tiny plunger now
knows what the card is...

05:35.067 --> 05:36.067
I didn't want to touch it.

05:36.133 --> 05:37.700
And he knows the order of the deck,

05:37.800 --> 05:39.300
so he should be able to do the following.

05:41.067 --> 05:42.300
Oh, come on!

05:45.767 --> 05:47.333
JON: Tiny plunger.

05:47.467 --> 05:48.667
I love this act!

05:48.800 --> 05:49.800
Thank you!

05:50.133 --> 05:51.133
I love it!

05:51.267 --> 05:53.033
One last time, one last time,
because I don't want you

05:53.100 --> 05:54.133
walking out of here thinking
I'm doing this.

05:54.200 --> 05:55.300
It's not me, it's him.

05:55.367 --> 05:56.367
I know! I know it's him!

05:56.433 --> 05:58.533
Yeah, it's him.
I'm his manager, but nothing else.

05:58.633 --> 06:00.100
So I'll prove it.

06:00.167 --> 06:02.200
If you wouldn't mind, Teller,
please touch a card.

06:02.433 --> 06:04.767
Pick it right out of there. Thank you.

06:04.933 --> 06:07.933
And now, again, I'll hide my
eyes so I can't see anything.

06:08.367 --> 06:09.767
But the plunger's looking right at it.

06:09.900 --> 06:11.600
Oh... Oh, really?

06:11.667 --> 06:13.433
-Yeah.
-Oh.

06:13.500 --> 06:15.033
Oh, yeah, he saw it. Sorry.

06:15.100 --> 06:18.000
Uh, here, hide the plunger
in your hand so he can't see it.

06:18.200 --> 06:19.433
Excellent. And just go ahead

06:19.500 --> 06:21.400
and just reach in there for me
and grab out a new one?

06:21.533 --> 06:22.767
Got it? Excellent.

06:22.967 --> 06:25.000
All right, show that card around
to everybody, and I won't look.

06:26.167 --> 06:27.300
Good, good, good!

06:27.367 --> 06:29.533
Excellent. And, uh...

06:29.600 --> 06:33.100
You could just place it back
inside here wherever you like.

06:33.567 --> 06:35.567
And that's where you wanted it, right?

06:35.633 --> 06:37.400
I'm not changing its location?

06:37.467 --> 06:38.900
I'm not even gonna shuffle.

06:40.667 --> 06:42.267
-May I have it?
-Yeah.

06:42.433 --> 06:43.433
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

06:44.600 --> 06:49.333
Last time, the plunger
had to be spoken to, to know the card.

06:49.867 --> 06:51.633
You don't speak as much, so this case,

06:51.700 --> 06:53.067
the plunger, yeah, will read your mind.

06:53.167 --> 06:54.367
Hold on... Yeah, go ahead.

06:54.800 --> 06:55.967
Uh, concentrate.

06:56.167 --> 06:57.567
(LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE)

06:58.433 --> 06:59.567
Concentrate.

07:00.100 --> 07:02.600
Hold on. Done.

07:03.467 --> 07:04.767
It goes away in about a week.

07:04.833 --> 07:05.867
All right.

07:05.933 --> 07:08.233
Now, he's a sentient plunger.
He knows what he wants.

07:08.300 --> 07:09.833
So, you're gonna do this for me, not me.

07:09.900 --> 07:11.900
The plunger and you
are just gonna go bonk, bonk.

07:12.133 --> 07:16.600
Bonk, bonk. And when you do that, he will
cut, hopefully, back directly to the card.

07:25.033 --> 07:26.333
JON: Tiny plunger.

07:26.433 --> 07:27.533
Thank you very much.

07:28.467 --> 07:31.800
JONATHAN:
That was quite something, wasn't it?

07:32.033 --> 07:33.367
Holy Moly!

07:35.200 --> 07:37.033
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

07:40.833 --> 07:41.833
So...

07:42.433 --> 07:45.100
Here's the cool thing, now. I'm allowed
to sit at the table with the guys,

07:45.167 --> 07:49.000
and I could hear... I could see Penn
just like, uh, amazed by it,

07:49.067 --> 07:50.133
and he was groaning sometimes,

07:50.200 --> 07:51.233
'cause you could see he was getting...

07:51.300 --> 07:53.467
And Teller was laughing at the whole thing
and loving every second of it.

07:53.533 --> 07:56.100
I don't think they have
the faintest idea yet how you did that,

07:56.167 --> 07:57.567
so you're in with a good chance, I think.

07:57.633 --> 07:59.033
-Maybe.
-Can I touch the plunger?

07:59.100 --> 08:00.200
-Yeah, of course!
-Okay.

08:00.267 --> 08:02.133
I'm want to ask the audience,
has anyone ever seen anything

08:02.200 --> 08:04.600
quite that small get such
a big reaction before?

08:06.033 --> 08:08.300
That really was quite something.

08:08.367 --> 08:10.033
Let me ask you something
else about yourself, because...

08:10.100 --> 08:11.200
And this struck a note with me.

08:11.267 --> 08:13.167
You were pretty severely
dyslexic when you were young.

08:13.233 --> 08:15.633
That is very true. I'm still dyslexic.
I'm extremely dyslexic.

08:15.700 --> 08:16.800
My children were both with that as well.

08:16.867 --> 08:17.967
I know it poses a lot of challenges.

08:18.033 --> 08:20.167
Did it help or hinder
the magic in any way?

08:20.233 --> 08:23.500
I think, in some ways,
it obviously hindered it,

08:23.567 --> 08:25.567
because of me reading from books.
It was very hard.

08:25.633 --> 08:27.933
But in some ways, it makes me
think of the world differently,

08:28.000 --> 08:31.133
and that's where weird things
like coming up with a plunger card trick,

08:31.200 --> 08:32.332
-that's all where it came from.
-Yeah.

08:32.400 --> 08:34.067
You know, when one struggles
through something like that,

08:34.133 --> 08:36.500
to come out the other side,
and be as good as somebody as you are,

08:36.567 --> 08:37.866
-that must feel just tremendous.
-Thank you.

08:37.933 --> 08:39.133
Are you ready for me to come to you guys?

08:39.200 --> 08:42.667
Uh, there's supposed
to be suspense at this moment,

08:42.866 --> 08:46.033
but I will say, right off the bat,
you did not fool me.

08:46.367 --> 08:48.533
-JON: Okay.
-But that little plunger did.

08:49.333 --> 08:50.933
But me... Me!

08:51.200 --> 08:53.033
The little plunger fooled me.

08:53.133 --> 08:57.367
I also don't know how to say this
with enough intensity,

08:57.733 --> 09:01.033
but maybe the only

09:01.267 --> 09:04.033
original card trick I've ever seen.

09:04.100 --> 09:07.533
Oh, wow, thank you.
Thank you, thank you. Oh.

09:08.633 --> 09:12.667
And also, the impression you get is,
you don't really touch the cards,

09:12.733 --> 09:14.333
it's the plunger doing all that.

09:14.400 --> 09:17.367
And there's something
so fair and so wonderful

09:17.533 --> 09:20.800
and just so whimsical
about the whole thing.

09:21.000 --> 09:25.333
The bad news is, about 40 years ago,
I teamed up with this guy.

09:25.400 --> 09:26.567
(LAUGHING) Yeah, right.

09:26.633 --> 09:30.900
And this guy has done very close
to a version of that trick,

09:31.000 --> 09:32.967
and even though it took my breath away,

09:33.033 --> 09:35.600
even though I needed a breather...

09:35.667 --> 09:38.133
Teller actually saw me taking...

09:38.200 --> 09:39.833
Being taken aback,

09:39.900 --> 09:41.633
and my breath being sucked in,

09:41.700 --> 09:45.400
and that gave him a big hint as to how
you put the whole thing together.

09:45.467 --> 09:47.800
Did not fool Teller. I loved this act!

09:47.867 --> 09:49.467
JON: Ah, thank you very much.

09:49.533 --> 09:51.700
Let me step in for just a second, though,

09:51.867 --> 09:53.500
because when Penn was talking,

09:53.567 --> 09:55.167
I noticed you, momentarily...

09:55.233 --> 09:56.667
You shook your head,
and I got the feeling...

09:56.733 --> 09:58.600
Oh, no, no, no, he... They're...
He knows how it works.

09:58.667 --> 10:00.533
I'm just extremely honored.
This is awesome,

10:00.600 --> 10:02.000
and thank you very much for having me on.

10:02.067 --> 10:03.400
Oh, what a great routine!

10:03.800 --> 10:06.067
So you did not fool them,
but thank you so much.

10:06.200 --> 10:08.867
Jon Armstrong and his tiny plunger,
ladies and gentlemen!

10:08.933 --> 10:10.900
-Thank you, Jon.
-(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

10:16.000 --> 10:17.800
Let's meet out next contender.

10:23.033 --> 10:24.033
<i>Bonjour.</i>

10:24.300 --> 10:25.333
<i>Hi, everyone.</i>

10:25.433 --> 10:28.133
My name is Xavier Mortimer,
and I'm from France.

10:29.900 --> 10:33.133
I'm so happy to be here in
Las Vegas, the city of magic.

10:33.200 --> 10:35.533
<i>A few years ago,</i>
<i>I was performing in Edinburgh.</i>

10:35.633 --> 10:37.300
In this festival, Cirque du Soleil saw me,

10:37.900 --> 10:41.167
<i>and they asked me if I wanted</i>
<i>to come and perform with them.</i>

10:41.233 --> 10:44.967
And I abandon
all my life that I had in Paris

10:45.033 --> 10:47.667
<i>to join one of the best</i>
<i>company in the world.</i>

10:49.800 --> 10:54.933
<i>I like card tricks and classic magic,</i>
<i>but what I love is showing people</i>

10:55.000 --> 10:57.033
<i>something that they</i>
<i>have never seen before.</i>

10:57.133 --> 11:00.100
<i>More than just fooling,</i>
<i>it's about entertainment.</i>

11:00.167 --> 11:02.100
<i>I like to bring people</i>
<i>to a different world,</i>

11:02.333 --> 11:03.867
<i>without using words,</i>

11:04.067 --> 11:07.767
because movement
and emotion is international.

11:07.900 --> 11:09.333
It's not just about the trick.

11:09.433 --> 11:13.900
At the end of the day, I just want them
to say that they saw something beautiful.

11:14.667 --> 11:16.467
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

11:20.133 --> 11:24.533
Our next performer grew up in Paris,
under the shadow of the real Eiffel Tower,

11:24.633 --> 11:26.967
dreaming of a day he could
perform magic here in Las Vegas,

11:27.067 --> 11:29.067
under the shadow of the fake Eiffel Tower.

11:29.167 --> 11:32.300
Will you join me in saying
<i>bonne chance</i> to Xavier?

11:32.567 --> 11:34.267
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

11:40.200 --> 11:41.833
(LOUD THUD)

11:42.767 --> 11:44.767
(EERIE MUSIC PLAYING)

